Pneumococal vaccine will be free and voluntary
The pneumococal vaccine from January will put an end to the usual customs.
As a first vaccine it should be free for families and at the same time voluntary.
However, there are already opinions that the compulsory vaccine would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of the free pneumococcal vaccine culminate.
The Institute for Medicines is already setting the maximum prices for vaccines, which will be covered by insurance companies.
The experts are also clear about this in the vaccination procedure.
The new vaccine
Free vaccinations for children born in August
From January onwards, children born on 2 August last year will be able to receive the pneumococal vaccine free of charge.
The condition is that you have not received a dose of the vaccine before.
Those who started the vaccine last year or before, have to cover other doses of the vaccine as well.
The first dose of the vaccine has to be received between the third and fifth months of age of the child.
Last year, one quarter of families voluntarily let their children vaccinate against pneumococci.
Parents, however, paid for a dose of 1600 crowns and more.
Four doses are needed to vaccinate younger children.
Experts generally estimate that insurance companies will spend 300 to 450 thousand kroner per year on vaccines.
However, they will save on treatment, which is needed for unvaccinated children.
So far, the state spent approximately 500,000 annually on all vaccinations for children.
The covered vaccination was initiated by the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococcal is the cause of otitis media, but also of serious infections including meningitis and septicaemia.
From pneumococal infections in our country every year 28 children not over 10 years of age die according to research in hospitals.
In addition to the Czech Republic, the pneumococal vaccine cover in children was introduced in approximately 40 countries.
Will the vaccine be mandatory?
However at the same time opinions appear, that this vaccine could be mandatory in future.
As of January it must be covered by insurance and voluntary companies.
The mandatory vaccine would be better, for example Rudolf Kalovský, the head of the Nahlas civic association.
Its association has been spreading pneumococal vaccines for a long time.
The experts at an international conference, in which our association participated, were not completely satisfied with the fact that we have the voluntary vaccine.
It's not completely ideal.
On the other hand we are happy, to achieve at least this.
I believe that this is the path that we now have to take, Kalovský mentioned.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the vaccination procedure against pneumococci.
At this moment we do not think about it at all, said its spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
Voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages, doctors say
