A gradual relief
Written in the country's constitution in 1978, the policy of a single son of China is possibly the most controversial mandate introduced to date by the Communist Party.
Couples who violate politics face huge fines, up to three times their annual salary in some areas, and labor discrimination.
Chinese officials have endorsed the policy for its contribution to avoid critical pressure on their natural resources, while human rights defenders have denounced abuses in the imposition of policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women with a second child to undergo abortions.
In addition, many couples have performed abortions according to the sex of the fetus, leading to a high unnatural male-female ratio.
In recent years, demographic officials have gradually softened their stance on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule, including urban residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases in which both husband and wife are single children, and in 2007 reduced many of their hard-line slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Beijing University's Institute of Demographic Research, said central government officials have recently been discussing even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the spouses is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Almost in the morning, the posters ordering families to have a single child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who would be suitable for a second child and how to apply for a permit.
The city government sent family planning officials and volunteers to visit couples in their homes and slide leaflets under the doors.
He has also promised to provide emotional and financial guidance to those who have chosen to have more than one child.
Family planning officials say the response has been very little overwhelming.
Disappointing response
Although rural city officials outside Shanghai argue that they observed a moderate increase in applications from couples who want a second child after the launch of the campaign, the more urban districts do not indicate any change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, is still receiving only four to five applications per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that, despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to reach only about 165,000, slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Caolu municipality's family planning committee in Shanghai, said financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don't want more children.
They want to give their first child their best, he said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and are legally entitled to do so.
But like many Chinese, they have only the inadequate health and life insurance provided to them by the government.
Without a social safety net, they argue, that option would be irresponsible.
People in the West incorrectly view the one-child policy as a matter of rights, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant from the couple's first child.
Yeah, we're being robbed of the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just a political issue.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their doubts.
Wang, the human resources manager, said he wants an only child because she too was: "We were the center of our families and we were used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to taking care of others and we really don't want to take care of others."
Chen Zijian, 42, owner of a translation agency, explained this more forcefully.
For parents with two careers, middle class, who reduce the birth rate, he said, it's about having enough success to be selfish.
People between the ages of 20 and 30 grew up watching their parents' struggle during the early days of China's experiment with capitalism and do not want that kind of life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child requires a lot of parental time, he said.
A mother has to give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are space issues, "they have to remodel their apartment," and the strategic one "must have a curriculum prepared for the best day care centers when the child is 9 months old."
“Most of his friends are willing to face this once,” Chen said, but not twice.
Ours is the first generation with the highest standard of living, he said.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, characterized so far by defiant positions and mutual recriminations, caught renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that foresees ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying on their shoulders most of the burden in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Prepared by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not speak of how much money rich countries would give the poor to face global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what the limit of the global temperature rise political strategists would be willing to tolerate.
This gives the process a lot of flexibility, said John Coequyt, high representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the top UN climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as "the big picture."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 25 to 45 per cent by 2020, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would cut their emissions during the same period by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would cut emissions by 50-95% by 2050.
The European Union also stimulated talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years, to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, Friday was presented the same kind of verbal fireworks that have dominated the conversations last week.
US Special Climate Envoy Todd Stern rejected claims calling for mandatory cuts in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China, with regard to what Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not make an agreement without the major developing countries moving forward and taking action, Stern said, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his remarks an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei claimed that America's top climate negotiator lacked "common sense," or was "very irresponsible" because he said earlier this week that the United States would not help China economically to cope with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, fault lines have erupted both within the developing world, as well as between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the bravest action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it is not surprising that the major powers are discussing who should pay for spending to limit greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in seeking to contain the big emitters responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is developing, said Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change advisor for Mexico and Central America, for Conservation International.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, even though most of the key participants would say that the talks would produce at most a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, prepared a preliminary 24-page treaty proposal early on Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who leads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said the push of small island nations has "put political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now unified and demand action from emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the exceptional issues before the heads of government come to close a deal.
High-level officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Vice Minister, descended from the planes and ran to the corridors of the Bella Center, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, so that they could delimit the claims that will be arbitrated during the coming week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where 13,000 people enter and leave the convention center every day, activists playing the guitar present night shows mocking the countries that they say are selling, and preliminary proposals are passed from hand to hand instead of via mail), poses a challenge.
The intensity only builds: almost all key ministers are here right now, and on Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, vice president for the global policy of Conservation International.
Heavyweights are coming in.
Britain’s first 225 km/h train redefines that feeling of Monday
At 5.13 on Monday morning, a whistle will pierce the darkness to signal a train exit marking a revolution for travel in Britain.
The country's first high-speed intercity train will reach 225 km/h, when it passes like lightning from Ashford, Kent, to St Panrcas Station in London, covering 93 kilometers in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Secretary of Transportation, will then be joined by Lady Kelly Holmes, aboard the first Javelin intercity service outside London.
He hopes that the new service will finally connect Britain to an international network of fast, reliable trains and connect the great conurbations of the Midlands, North and Scotland to London.
The neglected remote areas would become prosperous suburbs, business travel times would be shortened, and the switch from aircraft and cars to the railway would reduce national coal emissions, as well as ease congestion on roads.
In theory, the three main political parties believe in this vision.
But the tens of billions of pounds needed to build a new national railway network, the inevitable battle of planning and fears about environmental damage, can still slow Britain’s high-speed lines.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company set up in January to provide the government with a feasibility study, will deliver its report to Lord Adonis on December 30, according to the Times.
This will provide you with a detailed itinerary of the next stage planned for the high-speed network.
The new line linking London to the West Midlands will be drawn within a five-metre radius in urban areas and areas where the environmental impact may be controversial.
In rural areas, the plan will be drawn up within a radius of 25 metres of a definitive route.
HS2 is also expected to establish three options for a wider high-speed network heading north.
Lord Adonis will respond in spring.
The favored option being proposed is a Y-shaped configuration, in which a single high-speed line would reach the West Midlands.
The line would be divided into or near Birmingham, with a branch heading west from the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland, and another heading north-east to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line would enter Scotland.
"It seems that this will be the most beneficial option," said one member of the railway.
Once finished, travel times between London and Edinburgh would be reduced to 2 hours and 40 minutes.
The first stage, which would not be opened before 2025, would allow passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to just over one hour today.
The proposals would allow trains to travel at 402 km/h, making the British network the fastest in Europe.
The initial track is being designed to support 400 mt long trains, capable of transporting 1,100 people.
At least 18 trains could operate every hour on a London-Birmingham line.
This means that a London terminal capable of receiving 20,000 passengers per hour would be needed.
Considering the space constraints of the capital, it is expected that an existing station will be expanded to fit the high-speed network.
Experts in the railway industry argue that only St Pancras International or Euston station offer this potential.
Lord Adonis will announce if he believes that the scheme should proceed, but extensive public consultation and planning procedures mean that no final decision will be made until after a general election.
Even if it starts the work, the network would have to be built into sections.
Trains would initially be forced to leave the fast lines along the existing lanes north of Birmingham, keeping travel times between London and Scotland above three hours.
This is seen as the crucial point necessary to ensure a change from aircraft to trains, a reference point for the railway revolution.
Taxpayers face mortgage for an orange grove of £75,000 from a Conservative
Alan Duncan, the spokesman for the Conservative Party, charged the taxpayer thousands of pounds a year for the cost of an orange tree he built in his constituency home.
The party's prison spokesman, who was demoted by David Cameron for complaining that MPs lived "on rations," increased his mortgage by £75,000 to build an oak-framed extension in his second home in Rutland.
They allowed the taxpayer to charge the extra interest, adding hundreds of pounds a month.
The House of Commons authorities approved the applications at the time and have not been consulted by Sir Thomas Legg, who conducts a review of members' expenses. Last night Mr Duncan said that the requests "could not be clearer or simpler".
Mr. Duncan, one of the richest Members of Parliament, owns a two-story house in a village in his Rutland and Melton constituency.
The houses nearby have been sold for almost a million pounds.
The ground floor comprises a kitchen, living room and dining room, but the fee office agreed that Mr. Duncan needed more space.
Last year he added a greenhouse to the house, described in the plans as an "orange".
Neighbors described it as "a greenhouse for entertainment."
Mr. Duncan was not asked to make any reference to the increase in the loan, during a recent investigation by the House of Commons Committee on Standards and Privileges into his previous mortgage agreements.
Last month the committee acquitted him of violating the rules, after an investigation of his expenses.
In 2004, Mr. Duncan changed the legal guarantee for a mortgage of Pound271,406 from his London property to his constituency house, which he had purchased in 1991, the year before becoming a deputy.
Documents released this week show that Mr. Duncan was applying for approximately £1,400 a month in mortgage interest until March last year.
In April, their applications increased to more than £1,800 per month.
The interest rate on Mr Duncan's Royal Bank of Scotland mortgage did not change at the time, suggesting that the entire increase would finance the loan of £75,000.
The standard variable mortgage rate of the BRE fell from 7.94% in December 2007, to 4% in March of this year, which is now in place.
The most recent document issued by the House of Commons authorities shows that Mr Duncan continued to apply for £1,250 per month in May.
Duncan lost his job as president of the House's opposition in September, after an undercover reporter filmed him saying that MPs had to survive "rations" after the spending scandal.
"Basically this is nationalized, you have to live on rations and be treated as m**rda."
