And I could ask for a lot more, but I don't."
The deputy, a millionaire for his former profession as an oil trader, was questioned first about his expenses in May, when it turned out that he had requested thousands of pounds for his garden, before agreeing with the salary office that this "could be considered excessive."
An activist dug a hole in the shape of the sterling symbol on Mr. Duncan's lawn as a protest, revealing that he applied for £4,000 for three years.
Last night, when asked about the increase in the mortgage, Mr Duncan said, "It was for primordial improvements, approved both by the wage office and later by Legg."
He added: "It's not about circumventing and offending or breaking the rules or whatever.
This is absolutely within limits, according to the rules, authorized and all.
It could not in any way be clearer or simpler."
