Management revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of the big companies towards their employees recalls the position of the companies with regard to the consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of the collaborators adhering to "values" determined from above as before was to impose on the consumers products thought by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to the strategies of conquest of the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that have no relation to the factors of preference of the customers is repeated regularly.
A demobilisation of employees may result in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R & D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, the BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive conduct and a forward-looking vision"; it needs a commitment on the part of employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we called for a management revolution, which would be to put collaborators at the heart of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, incite the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I could verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many turns, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
Second, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behavioral theory that American "neurosciences" recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely spread behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent research of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management posture, unsuitable to today's world.
Identifying and measuring mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies means adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists in integrating into any reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to make part of their dreams, ambitions and projects a reality.
Nowadays, only the studies from the Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of the motivations of the employees.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
By identifying and measuring mobilisation factors, business managers can monitor, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resources management "in place".
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
Oslo speech: Obama receives praise from the right wing for the "just war"
This Friday, the American right wing, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize has defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States, hailed the speech Obama had delivered on Thursday.
Conservatives, who had discredited the Obama award on October 9, this time applauded the presidential speech, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate during the 2008 elections.
I loved what she said, said Mrs.Palin, a leading figure in the right wing of the Republican party to the USA Today newspaper, and added that she herself had addressed the issue of war "sometimes necessary" in her recently published memoirs.
In my opinion, war is, of course, the last thing the Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
“The terrorists must be stopped,” he observed.
Obama, who inherited the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, dedicated himself, this Thursday in Oslo, to justifying the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 more soldiers to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another Obama opponent, Newt Gingrich, considered that the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I think the speech was really very good, the former president of the House of Representatives was happy, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential words.
At times, the speech seemed very historic to me, Gingrich said, during an interview on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former elected representative, who some consider as a possible candidate for the Republican investiture for the 2012 presidential election, was pleased to hear "a leftist president" when he reminded the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and could not deliver a peace prize if the use of force did not exist."
