After three sessions of marathon negotiations, the trade unions of the road sector and the TLF (Transport and Logistics of France), the only employers' organization that remained until the end, arrived on Friday afternoon at an agreement that puts an end to the strike slogan and the threat that falls on the Christmas supply.
During the signing session on Friday night, Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, was "joyed" by the agreement, after several negotiating sessions that began on Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, the negotiators said goodbye at the dawn of Friday in the hope of quickly signing the text in agreement at the end of the morning.
Even though three employers' organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) withdrew by slamming the door.
But a meeting of more than six hours that began at 11 a.m. was necessary for everyone to agree and the text to be signed at 6 p.m.
The conflict "would have been very damaging to businesses" and "was feared that it would disturb the end-of-year holidays," Bussereau said.
The text provides for an increase of 4 per cent for lower wages (in local and regional road transport) and 2.9 per cent for higher wages (international transport).
The hourly rate rises from 8.72 euros to 9.06 euros for low wages.
“It’s not much, but we started with a lot of disadvantage,” Patrice Clos (FO) explained.
If so, we will give the order to our militants that there should be no more cuts or blockades in the supply centres.
But there may always be some dissenting rebel, he added.
