Bussereau recalled that "a drop of 100 million euros in employer charges" was the subject of a government amendment in the draft rectification finance law for 2009, which the National Assembly voted on Thursday night.
The government will ask the Senate to vote on it "on the same terms."
TLF's signature allows the agreement to apply, first, to companies affiliated to this organisation and, secondly, to the entire profession, should the Minister of Labour extend it.
It will be done "as soon as possible," said Bussereau.
Opposition from employers' organizations could only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced that it was a "naive business", since the 100 million euros "had already been promised to the sector to offset part of the CO2 tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate in an emergency situation, not as a conclusion to an analysis discussed by the parties, but not to oppose those who wish to eat turkey at the next Christmas Eve dinner, the Unostra lamented.
For OTRE, the agreement puts at risk "the stability of many SMEs in the sector over the next 12 months".
