Turkish justice dissolves the prokurdo party, a decision with serious consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled Friday in favour of the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that immediately provoked demonstrations of anger in the Kurdish community, in the south-eastern part of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community trying to put an end to 25 years of conflict.
The party of the Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become the "focus of activities that harmed the independence of the State and its indivisible unity," Court President Hasim Kiliç told the press after four days of deliberations.
The decision of the 11 judges was unanimous, although only a seven-vote majority was needed to obtain dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's leaders, including its president Ahmet Türk and deputy Aysel Tugluk, are separated from political life for five years.
The judge also announced the cessation of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Türk and Tugluk, and the confiscation of the party's assets by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament ( 550).
Its leaders warned prior to the verdict that the MPs would leave Parliament before they were parliamentary without party labels.
The decision arose from a procedure launched by Supreme Court prosecutor Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya in 2007, accusing the DTP of obeying the "principles" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many other countries.
Numerous observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
However, the party claims that it has no "organic links" with the PKK, but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The Court's verdict intervenes at a time when the government lends a hand to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen their rights, so that the Kurds stop supporting the PKK and thus put an end to the conflict.
The DTP leaders stated that a dissolution could lead to a resurgence of tensions in South-East Anatolian, where a large number of demonstrations against the conditions of detention of PKK chief Abdullah Öcalan degenerated into clashes with the police over the past few weeks.
