The forces of the Order threw tear gas grenades and used water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov cocktails or stones with slingshots.
In Istanbul, about a hundred people were also concentrated.
After the verdict, Türk stated that the decision of the justice system was to "deepen discouragement."
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurda, NDLR) by dissolving a party, he told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also regrets the decision.
In principle, we oppose the closure of parties.
Thus nothing is resolved, declared Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision completely boycotts the democratic opening launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK was awarded an attack in which seven soldiers were killed three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the bloodiest attacks in recent months.
