In a waking state, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the case of the mentally ill and drug addicts do the boundaries between imagination and reality fade away.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can unfetteredly surrender ourselves to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, those who experience sleep-like states during the vigil, or see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are considered most of the time in the modern Western world as crazy or drug addict, or at least as maniac.
But such images and voices not only arise in the mentally ill or in the drugged.
Our imagination blames it: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, sometimes cause the boundaries between sleep, madness and reality to blur.
The states of alertness modified dreamly can appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, madness.
Although the triggers and effects can be distinguished, similar processes can be referred to the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the prophet of the New Age Carlos Castañeda, the states of shamanic possession, and the psychoses and hallucinations.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain – especially dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine – has been derailed and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disturbed.
During a schizophrenic psychosis complex hallucinations and crazy thoughts often appear.
Gravity no longer has power over him.
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and doctors since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived the hallucinations as a form of waking dream, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great similarity of the state of madness with the dream states", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the dispurposes, mad formations, and mirages of it".
