His body is two dimensions and scandalously colorful.
Gravity no longer has power over it, it's floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, demon figures with wings, with red faces like blood, deformed, gnashing teeth.
They're chasing him, kicking him with heavy, flaming boots, throwing him into the walls, he feels the pains all over his body.
Shrill and evil voices echo from the walls and the radio.
He can no longer stand them, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. pulls two wires out of the stereo, ties them to form a hanger's knot, and fixes them on a hook on the ceiling.
It goes up in a horn and puts the knot around the neck.
Jump.
The rope is loose.
Let it be a lesson to you!The voices shout in a chorus that blows his eardrums, "Go to the clinic and have them heal you!"
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychosis, the last one two years ago, the first one almost 20 years ago.
The cause that produced it was LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, plus he is manic-depressive, he takes medications, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, for three years he has been married.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in the life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most frequent disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside and the inside world, and fall into a state of overexcitation that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, relationship disorders, or persecution mania.
Especially widespread is the hearing of voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter the disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis also opens the floodgates to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the general psychiatry clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning aimed at him.
At the same time it enters into a passive role, as in a dream, it feels overwhelmed by events and cannot organize them actively.
That is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, awakening, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, "the spatial and sensory structure of reality perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is."
The paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the distancing of experience takes place in reality.
For the researchers still a little unknown why our brain makes cabriolas.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can lead anyone to lose contact with reality on a temporary basis.
But not all people develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes there are also other determinants.
Researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the brain's neuronal maturity is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a mother's viral disease during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it is still unknown how this alteration of the neural system occurs, which also does not manifest at all for many years.
Also the influence of the environment plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when there is already a prior disposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis, as they interfere with the transmitting system of the brain.
When the brain warms up
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer from their hallucinations and take very expensive medicines to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says Professor of Psychology Erich Kasten, from Lübeck.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf, published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
These include, together with psychic disorders such as personality-limit disorder or depressions, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's and head injury .
surprisingly and under certain conditions, the brain of healthy people also suffers hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are composed of memories that are usually repressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or poorly inhibited; when our brain is hot, but also when stimuli are lacking.
Drugs can cause this state in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the restriction of stimuli, stress, love sickness or other states of emergency.
