I think the brain is unemployed and takes care of it for entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was in little fear of the other children and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at the age of 13, he learned that the man he calls Dad since he has used reason is not his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, it is difficult for those affected like Sarah K. to distinguish between visions and reality. "Each experience," says Kasten, "it takes place in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are equally images that the brain produces, so they seem so real."
Kasten also classifies night fantasies as a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, psychically healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends that his patients appreciate his hallucinations as a special skill.
Situation borderline between sleep and hallucination
In this world too focused on the conscious, imaginary experiences are usually pathological, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a harsh and painful illness but it also involves something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated the so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as if it were a dream.
The dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers to be real and that later cannot tell from being awake.
The dream conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis being fully conscious. die bei vollem Bewusstsein eine motorische Lähmung erleben.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of oneself or the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, it replaces a very dangerous real situation with a world of its own and imaginary that is decoupled from reality.
A form of situation border between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, there is a change in the world, although the real situation is still present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an inexhaustible situation in itself that our own capacity for creation allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Also art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen of Zurich describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as an action to save the soul.
He was 49 years old, when his conscience embarked on journeys of several days after an operation of heart valves with heart transplant included, while his body was doomed to immobility at the intensive care station.
Claussen plunged into a world created by him and visited strange places of other times: he was prostrate in bed, an older man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot was watching for his health.
It was seen in the high Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorcycle kidnapped him in his home country, surfed his hospital bed in the Alps with top snow and met a Korean mobster.
It gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, describes your experience.
