Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women from younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fecundity and career path of women in Spain', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75 per cent of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to maternity.
The study points out that there are many differences in the beginning of the couple's cohabitation and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have a non-stable job, first start living together, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay coexistence and motherhood, and have less offspring.
"Women between 35 and 49 years of age with fixed work have the first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting the cohabitation, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time of their life trajectory to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of the children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a lot of influence on motherhood, although less on the timing of the pairing," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that differentiates the age of women when they are married and when they have the first stem.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the older the age at which they marry and the age at which they have the first child.
The difference also remains among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at an average of 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
"Another division is also established among women according to their level of education.
While those with elementary education marry and have their first child before they get a steady job, those with middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child," Delgado explains.
