Emergency braking aid is already mandatory
As was the case with ABS anti-lock braking and will pass with ESP stability control, emergency braking support systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they already are in all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a period of lack is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, by its way of work, it can also help to avoid many collisions by scope.
The emergency braking assistant does what it does is increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the stomp given by the driver.
But this one doesn't always hold that pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by the Bosch car component manufacturer, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not stepped on the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, demands the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided annually.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four casualties would be avoided with damage to people - when the so-called intelligent emergency braking system becomes popular.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via a radar or camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and even if the collision is unavoidable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimise damage.
